<DOC><DOCNO> AP890729-0141 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-29-89 2353EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Violence     07-29 0256</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Peru-Violence,0264</SECOND><HEAD>Government Says 110 Maoist Guerrillas Killed in Battles with Army</HEAD><DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soldiers killed 110 guerrillas of the ShiningPath movement in three battles including one in which 60 rebels andseven soldiers died, the government reported Saturday.   It said the fighting occurred Thursday and Friday, during theIndependence Day holidays, in jungle areas northeast of Lima. Perucelebrated its 168th anniversary of independence from Spain onFriday.   A communique carried by the government's Andina news agency gavethis account of the battles:   Three army units clashed with a group of about 150 rebelsThursday near Madre Mia, 235 miles northeast of Lima in Huanucodistrict. Sixty guerrillas and seven soldiers were killed and 12troops wounded.   Thirty rebels were killed in a fight near the town of NuevoProgreso, 255 miles northeast of Lima, but the military did not sayif the army suffered any casualties.   In the third clash near Tulumayo, 220 miles northeast of thecapital and also in Huanuco, 20 rebels and one soldier were killedand one soldier was wounded.   The communique said the army captured large caches of armsfollowing the battles. It did not elaborate.   The government reported earlier this month that more than 100Shining Path guerrillas had been killed in Huanuco as army unitsand helicopters conducted a series of raids in a counterinsurgencyoperation.   The Maoist Shining Path began its campaign to overthrow thegovernment in 1980 and the government says more than 15,000 peoplehave been killed in the fighting.</TEXT></DOC>